w, the concept of statehood and the right of self-determination, the role of international institutions and the law of human rights. Concluding with a consideration of whether the inclusion of women in the jurisdiction of international war crimes tribunals represents a significant shift in the boundaries of international law, the book encourages a dramatic rethinking of the discipline of international law. With a new introduction that reflects on the profound changes in international law since the book’s first publication in 2000, this provocative volume is essential reading for scholars, practitioners and students alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminist jurisprudence. 0aInternational lawxSociological aspects. 0aInternational law. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc. 4aPolitical Studies 2022. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh  aInternational Law Commission.  aThe Women's Convention.  afeminist analysis.  afeminist jurisprudence.  afeminist perspective.  ahuman rights.  ainternational feminist perspective.  ainternational law.  aself-determination.  awomen's rights.1 aCharlesworth, Hilary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChinkin, Christine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aChinkin, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616359240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526163592423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526163592/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles